{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BRTmK2j3Rtgao3XDciTU5T","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"For the runs.html template, the select dropdown uses `.Dir` as the option value. The `filterByProject` JavaScript function takes this value and redirects. I need to change it so the option value is the label (or I keep the dir as value but add a data attribute for the label). \n\nActually, the cleanest approach: change the select option value to `.Label` and use that for the redirect URL. But then I also need `ProjectFilter` to be a label instead of a dir... Hmm, this is getting complex.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The new URL structure is `/projects/<label>/runs`. So:\n\n1. The route `GET /projects/{name}/runs` would use `resolveProjectDir` to get the dir from the label\n\n\n2. I could modify `handleRunsList` to check for a project name in the URL path first, then fall back to the query parameter, and use `resolveProjectDir` to handle missing projects with an appropriate error response for HTML.\n\nAdding the new routes... Still writing handler logic...\n\nNow I need to update the templates to use the label-based URLs instead of query parameters. In the project listing and detail pages, I'll change the run links to navigate to `/projects/{{.Label}}/runs`. For the runs page itself, I need to update the project selector dropdown to use labels as values, modify the filtering logic to navigate to the label-based URL, and adjust the polling endpoint accordingly.\n\nThe key insight is keeping `ProjectFilter` as a directory internally while exposing labels in the UI—I'll add a `ProjectFilterLabel` field to the template data so the dropdown and JavaScript can work with labels for navigation while the backend continues using directories. I'm realizing I should simplify this approach—instead of juggling multiple representations, I'll just update the handler to compute both the project filter and its label, pass both to the template, and use the label consistently for URL construction and API calls. This way the page navigates to `/projects/<label>/runs` and the polling API uses the same path-based pattern for consistency. - Modify handlers to check path variable first, then query param\n\n**Template changes for runs.html:**\n- Change select option value to label\n- Change `ProjectFilter` comparison to use label\n- Update JS to navigate to `/projects/<label>/runs`  \n- Update polling to use `/api/projects/<label>/runs`\n\n**Data changes:**\n- Pass `ProjectFilterLabel` to template alongside `ProjectFilter`\n- Or just pass the label and use it for everything\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach: just change the data so `ProjectFilter` is the label (when coming from path route) or derive the label when it's a dir (when coming from query param). Then everything in the template works with labels.\n\nWait, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me just:\n\n1. The handler resolves the project filter (from either path or query param) to a dir\n2. Also compute the label for that dir\n3. Pass both to the template\n4. Template uses label for URLs\n\nHere's my plan: I'm writing a handler that extracts the project filter from either the path parameter or query string, resolves it to a directory, and computes the corresponding label. If the filter comes from the path, I use the path name directly as the label. If it comes from a directory, I need to derive the label from that directory. I'm realizing I should simplify this by using the label consistently throughout instead of juggling between directory and label. I'll update the template data to pass `ProjectFilterLabel` as the filter value, then use that same label in the JavaScript for navigation and API calls—comparing against it directly without needing to look up data attributes or maintain separate variables.\n\nFor the handler, I'll add the new routes and resolve the label parameter to its corresponding directory so `ListRunsByProject` still receives what it expects.\n\nIn the templates, I'm switching to label-based URLs for filtering and polling, while storing the label in a data attribute so the JavaScript can use it properly.\n\nI'll also update the project links across all templates and make sure the tests reflect these URL changes.\n\nNow let me start implementing this.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":411,"cache_read_input_tokens":27933,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":411},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fc9fd8a8-bf87-49d2-bf62-1ae5b9ba4dc0","uuid":"63151beb-1b06-42e1-b077-ea35e70168ce"}
